## 3. Why frequent `WRITE_DISCARD` protects (and per-generation made it worse)

### (a) ~370 discards/frame on **one** `ID3D11Buffer` Ã¢â‚¬â€ playable

Each `Map(WRITE_DISCARD)` on the **same resource** asks the driver for a fresh physical allocation while **retaining old allocations for in-flight draws** on that resource. This is the documented D3D11 dynamic-buffer rename model. Your discard storm accidentally keeps slices isolated in separate rename generations **without you implementing fencing**.

The over-charge ensures discards fire constantly, so skinned slices rarely survive long enough in one physical page for GPU lag to catch up with CPU reuse.

### (b) ~1 discard/frame or per-generation buffers Ã¢â‚¬â€ broken

**Correct accounting:** ring fills once, many `WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE` appends share **one physical page** for most of the frame. D3D11 does **not** fence those appends against in-flight GPU reads the way D3D9 `Lock` did Ã¢â€ â€™ widespread corruption.

**Per-generation (N=4):** this is **not** the same as per-resource rename. With high discard pressure you cycle 4 buffers faster than GPU latency. A slice bound to `buffer[gen%4]` at `prepareToDraw` can have that buffer **reused for a later slice** before the draw executes Ã¢â‚¬â€ deterministic garbage, RenderDoc-capturable. You traded D3D11Ã¢â‚¬â„¢s deep per-resource rename chain for a shallow 4-buffer pool with **no fence**.

**Why per-generation Ã¢â€°Â  protective discard storm:**

```
One buffer, 370 DISCARD/frame:
  Resource R Ã¢â€ â€™ rename chain RÃ¢â€šâ‚¬, RÃ¢â€šÂ, RÃ¢â€šâ€š Ã¢â‚¬Â¦ (driver keeps all alive for in-flight draws)

N=4 generation pool:
  Gen0 written Ã¢â€ â€™ Gen1 written Ã¢â€ â€™ Ã¢â‚¬Â¦ Ã¢â€ â€™ Gen0 RECYCLED (only 4 deep)
  Draw still references Gen0 slice Ã¢â€ â€™ reads recycled memory Ã¢â€ â€™ deterministic corruption
```

