codex
**Findings**

1. **The D3D11 ring still has no real frame/resource lifetime discipline.**  
   D3D11 has `Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData::beginFrame()` at `Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:144`, but `update_impl()` is still a no-op at `Direct3d11.cpp:289`, and the wired `ms_glApi.update` points to that no-op at `Direct3d11.cpp:1011`. D3D9 does reset at `Direct3d9.cpp:2484-2486`.  
   That said, a naive per-frame reset is not sufficient if engine prepare and draw are separated across passes.

2. **D3D9 is not the same contract as D3D11 here.**  
   D3D9 locks a byte range: `Lock(ms_used, length, ..., D3DLOCK_NOOVERWRITE/DISCARD)` at `Direct3d9_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:207`, then draws with explicit vertex bounds: `DrawIndexedPrimitive(..., minimumVertexIndex, numberOfVertices, ...)` at `Direct3d9.cpp:4157`.  
   D3D11 maps the whole resource at `Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:268`, manually offsets the CPU pointer at `:281`, then draws with `DrawIndexed(..., BaseVertexLocation)` only, e.g. `Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:3225-3228`. The D3D11 runtime does not receive D3D9Ã¢â‚¬â„¢s `minimumVertexIndex/numberOfVertices` draw range. The app owns the full Ã¢â‚¬Å“never overwrite anything the GPU may still readÃ¢â‚¬Â promise.

3. **Frequent `WRITE_DISCARD` is plausibly protective because it delegates renaming to the driver.**  
   Baseline D3D11 overcharges UI locks because `CuiLayerRenderer` locks the whole remaining ring at `CuiLayerRenderer.cpp:64-68` but unlocks actual vertices at `:528`, `:548`, `:568`; current D3D11 advances `ms_used` in `lock()` by the upper bound at `Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:281-282` and explicitly does not adjust in `unlock()` at `:352-357`.  
   That causes many driver-managed renames. A manual 4-generation scheme is not equivalent. Driver renaming can hand out more backing storage and retire it when safe; a fixed generation cycle reuses by your counter, not by GPU fence completion.

4. **The RenderDoc transition is a major clue, but not proof of the original bug.**  
   Original Ã¢â‚¬Å“capture replays cleanÃ¢â‚¬Â fits async CPU/GPU reuse. Per-generation Ã¢â‚¬Å“capture replays dirtyÃ¢â‚¬Â means the dirty bytes existed in the submitted stream RenderDoc captured. That usually indicates the new code made corruption deterministic before capture: wrong generation bound, generation reused before deferred draw, offset/accounting bug, or data uploaded into one resource while draw reads another. It does not exonerate the original race; it says the attempted fix introduced or exposed a separate deterministic lifetime/binding failure.

5. **The core invariant to enforce is per-draw slice ownership, not just per-frame/per-discard buffers.**  
   Soft skin writes all vertices in `prepareToDraw()` via `m_dynamicStream->lock(m_vertexCount)` / `unlock()` at `SoftwareBlendSkeletalShaderPrimitive.cpp:575-580`, `:592-597`, `:614-619`, and renders later through `RenderCommand::render()` at `:306-315`. The actual soft loops write `i < m_vertexCount` at `:1640` and `:1690`, so partial CPU fill is unlikely. The weak point is lifetime of the uploaded bytes between prepare and the eventual indexed draw.

**Answers**

1. D3D9 works because its runtime receives tighter lock and draw-range information and has older implicit synchronization behavior. D3D11 `WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE` is a stricter no-sync contract. If your ring ever reuses bytes that a deferred draw has not consumed, D3D11 is allowed to tear.

2. Yes, the capture-invisible to capture-deterministic transition is key. It strongly suggests the per-generation patch was not a correct fix. It likely made a concrete stale-buffer/stale-offset/reused-generation state visible in the captured command stream.

3. Frequent discard protects because each discard asks the D3D11 driver for renamed backing memory. Manual N-generation buffers only protect if N is fence-retired, not merely round-robin. Four buffers can be worse than one driver-renamed buffer with a deeper/safer rename pool.

4. Correct discipline: a dynamic upload slice must not be recycled until every draw that references it has been submitted and the GPU has passed it. For deferred engine draws, either allocate/upload at actual draw submission time, or make the render command own the exact buffer+offset generation and retire it by fence.

5. Minimal correct fix I would choose: **isolate soft-skin positions from the shared UI ring**. Give soft-skinned primitives their own D3D11 dynamic buffer or small per-primitive/per-frame buffer set, bind offset 0, update with `WRITE_DISCARD`, and do not remap that primitiveÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s soft-skin buffer again until the next skin update. Keep `CuiLayerRenderer` on the shared ring. This matches the RenderDoc evidence: only soft-skin POSITION stream is bad, while UIÃ¢â‚¬â„¢s lock-all behavior is an accidental rename pump, not a design to preserve.

I would not reattempt fixed per-generation ring buffers unless they are fence-retired. A larger ring may reduce symptoms but still lacks the correctness property.
