codex
The right portable fence here is `D3D11_QUERY_EVENT`; this renderer is baseline `ID3D11Device`/immediate context, not a D3D11.4 fence API user. Iâ€™m going to answer with that as the primary mechanism and call out the places the proposed design needs tightening.
codex
**Verdict:** the proposed design is directionally correct, but only if it is strict: fixed buffers must be retired by a real GPU query, there must be no mid-frame `WRITE_DISCARD` on a buffer containing deferred slices, and overflow must not silently fall back to an unfenced scratch buffer.

The current D3D11 path still binds one global dynamic VB at both dynamic bind sites: `Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:2265` and `Direct3d11_VertexBufferVectorData.cpp:143`. Current lock also advances `ms_used` at lock time, not actual unlock time: `Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:279-282`, while unlock explicitly does not adjust it at `:352-357`. D3D9 does the opposite: lock records offset at `Direct3d9_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:207,217`, then advances by actual count at `:231-244`. Fix that as part of this design or `CuiLayerRenderer.cpp:64-68` will keep poisoning allocator behavior.

**Fence Mechanism**

Use `ID3D11Query` with `D3D11_QUERY_EVENT`. Do not use `ID3D11Fence` as the primary path. `ID3D11Fence` requires newer D3D11.4-style interfaces (`ID3D11Device5` / `ID3D11DeviceContext4`) and is not guaranteed by this rendererâ€™s baseline `ID3D11Device` / immediate context setup (`Direct3d11_Device.h:39-40`, `Direct3d11_Device.cpp:448,471`). The repo already has a debug full-sync example using `D3D11_QUERY_EVENT` in `Direct3d11_Device.cpp:877-886`; use that pattern, but per buffer and only before reuse.

Signal placement: call `End(query)` after the frameâ€™s final draw submission and before `Present`. The natural hook is `Direct3d11_Device::present()` after the existing pre-present render flush comment at `Direct3d11_Device.cpp:853` and before `ms_swapChain->Present(1, 0)` at `:858`.

Wait placement: in the once-per-frame hook `update_impl()` (`Direct3d11.cpp:289`), before selecting/reusing that buffer. That hook is wired as `ms_glApi.update` at `Direct3d11.cpp:1011` and is before `beginScene`, which matters because `beginScene` is per-pass (`Direct3d11_Device.cpp:641`) and must not reset dynamic storage.

**Shape**

I would use **4 fixed buffers**, not 3, unless measurement proves 3 never stalls. Four 4 MB buffers is still only 16 MB and no churn. If close busy scenes overflow 4 MB, increase the fixed size to 8 MB or make it configurable. Do not use a 4th â€œscratchâ€ by unfenced discard; that recreates the bug in a different lane.

Within a frame:

```cpp
// first lock after beginFrame on this retired buffer
Map(currentBuffer, 0, D3D11_MAP_WRITE_DISCARD, 0, &mapped);

// subsequent locks in same frame
Map(currentBuffer, 0, D3D11_MAP_WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE, 0, &mapped);
```

Advance `ms_used` on `unlock(actualVertices)`, not on `lock(upperBound)`, so `CuiLayerRenderer` remains valid.

**Code Skeleton**

```cpp
static constexpr int kDynamicFrameBuffers = 4;
static Microsoft::WRL::ComPtr<ID3D11Buffer> ms_buffers[kDynamicFrameBuffers];
static Microsoft::WRL::ComPtr<ID3D11Query>  ms_done[kDynamicFrameBuffers];
static bool ms_donePending[kDynamicFrameBuffers];
static bool ms_bufferUsedThisFrame;
static bool ms_firstMapThisFrame;
static int  ms_currentBuffer;
```

```cpp
void Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData::beginFrame()
{
    int const next = (ms_currentBuffer + 1) % kDynamicFrameBuffers;
    waitForBuffer(next);

    ms_currentBuffer = next;
    ms_used = 0;
    ms_firstMapThisFrame = true;
    ms_bufferUsedThisFrame = false;
}
```

```cpp
void Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData::signalFrameFence()
{
    if (!ms_bufferUsedThisFrame)
        return;

    ID3D11DeviceContext *ctx = Direct3d11_Device::getContext();
    ctx->End(ms_done[ms_currentBuffer].Get());
    ms_donePending[ms_currentBuffer] = true;
}
```

```cpp
void Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData::waitForBuffer(int index)
{
    if (!ms_donePending[index])
        return;

    ID3D11DeviceContext *ctx = Direct3d11_Device::getContext();
    BOOL done = FALSE;

    for (;;)
    {
        HRESULT const hr = ctx->GetData(ms_done[index].Get(), &done, sizeof(done), 0);
        if (hr == S_OK)
            break;

        FATAL(FAILED(hr), ("dynamic VB fence GetData failed: %08x", hr));
        Sleep(0);
    }

    ms_donePending[index] = false;
}
```

**Critical Caveat**

If you guarantee one dynamic VB buffer per whole frame and fatal on overflow, existing `getSharedRingBuffer()` bind sites can return the current frame buffer. If you allow mid-frame overflow to another fixed buffer, slices must store their owning `ID3D11Buffer*`, and the bind sites at `Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:2265` and `Direct3d11_VertexBufferVectorData.cpp:143` must bind `data->getVertexBuffer()`, not the global current buffer. Otherwise old deferred slices will bind the wrong buffer.

**Simpler Fix?**

A single baseline ring plus one fence on wrap is only correct if the ring never wraps before all CPU-deferred draws referencing earlier bytes have been submitted. Your evidence says pass deferral exists, so a wrap/discard can invalidate not-yet-submitted slices; a GPU fence cannot wait for commands the CPU has not submitted. It may reduce cross-frame GPU races, but it is not the full fix.

D3D9 survives mostly because it has actual-used accounting (`Direct3d9_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:231-244`), far fewer wraps, and older `Lock` behavior. D3D11 `WRITE_NO_OVERWRITE` is a stricter promise: if you reuse bytes before every referencing draw has passed the GPU, the app is wrong.
